english:
  title: Autumn Night at Jiangshan Temple
  author: Suk Hongyon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    South of the great river stands Zhongshan Temple,
    Its towering pavilions exhale the fragrance of sandalwood.
    Beyond the clouds, as sutras are chanted, white cranes descend,
    Within the cave, a jade dragon coils, guarding the dharma.
    The pagoda's shadow trembles on the moonlit cliff at night,
    At dawn the temple bell mingles with the cold wind through the pines.
    The ancients say celestial beings gather here in multitudes—
    Even now I sense the tinkling of their jade ornaments, soft and clear.
  footnotes:
    - Jiangshan Temple (蔣山寺) is located near present-day Nanjing, historically one of the most important Buddhist temples in southern China.
    - The white cranes and jade dragon are traditional symbols of spiritual blessing and divine protection in Buddhist temple poetry.
    - The 'jade ornaments' (環佩) refer to the celestial adornments worn by heavenly beings, their jingling suggesting their presence.
